%I A397366 #41 Jul 13 2026 19:45:06
%S A397366 2,3,5,6,7,8,10,7,11,13,14,14,15,18,7,10,11,15,17,19,20,21,22,20,23,
%T A397366 26,15,23,27,29,30,23,26,31,32,34,17,19,23,29,31,34,35,37,38,32,39,42,
%U A397366 11,15,22,23,30,31,35,39,41,43,44,45,46,38,47,50
%N A397366 Irregular triangle S, related to the Erdős-Strauss conjecture.
%C A397366 For n > 0, S(n) denotes the set of integers A in {0, 1, 2, ..., 4*n-2} such that A*X + W == 0 (mod 4*n-1) for some positive integer divisors X and W of n.
%H A397366 OEIS Wiki, <a href="https://oeis.org/wiki/Erd%C5%91s%E2%80%93Straus_conjecture">Erdős-Straus conjecture</a>.
%H A397366 Serge E. Salez, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1406.6307">The Erdős-Straus conjecture; New modular equations and checking up to N = 10^17</a>, arXiv:1406.6307 [math.NT], 2014.
%H A397366 Alan Swett, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20140915073629/http://math.uindy.edu/swett/esc.htm">The Erdos-Strauss Conjecture</a>, 1999.
%H A397366 Alan Swett, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20140826084250/http://math.uindy.edu/swett/s_table.htm">Table of Values of S(n)</a>, 1999.
%H A397366 Alan Swett, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20140826093525/http://math.uindy.edu/swett/other_form.htm">Alternative Calculation of S(n)</a>, 1999.
%H A397366 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Erdos-StrausConjecture.html">Erdős-Straus Conjecture</a>.
%H A397366 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erd%C5%91s%E2%80%93Straus_conjecture">Erdős-Straus conjecture</a>.
%F A397366 The last term of the n-th row is 4*n-2: S(n)[#] = 4*n-2.
%F A397366 For n > 1, the n-th row contains the term 4*n-5, at position A083039(n) from the end: S(n)[#-A083039(n)] = 4*n-5.
%F A397366 No term is congruent to {0, 1, 4, 9} mod 12.
%e A397366 The initial 8 rows are:
%e A397366   1: 2;
%e A397366   2: 3, 5, 6;
%e A397366   3: 7, 8, 10;
%e A397366   4: 7, 11, 13, 14;
%e A397366   5: 14, 15, 18;
%e A397366   6: 7, 10, 11, 15, 17, 19, 20, 21, 22;
%e A397366   7: 20, 23, 26;
%e A397366   8: 15, 23, 27, 29, 30.
%e A397366 From Alan Swett's pages: "Looking at n = 7 for example, it follows that ESC(n) is true for every integer n which is congruent to 20, 23, or 26 (mod 27). For instance, ESC(47) is true, since 47 is congruent to 20 (mod 27)."
%o A397366 (PARI) S(n)= Set(divisors(n^2)*-4%(4*n-1));
%Y A397366 Cf. A000037, A083039, A192787, A396825.
%K A397366 nonn,tabf,new
